\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <h> <#/>Making use of others' miseries </h>
\par <#/>SINCE the last four weeks or so, I have been trying to think of a way of getting myself enlisted i
n the team which will be assigned to distribute food aid to either the flood victims in Kipatimu, Kilwa District or drought victims in Monduli District. <#/>To be in both teams will be a lot better.
\par <#/>There was this fellow I confided my plans in but ended up getting enlisted himself and left me in the cold. <#/><ea_><X_>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Kaniacha kwenye}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 mataa}{\i\fs24\lang2057 </X>}{\fs24\lang2057 <ea/>}{
\i\fs24\lang2057 !!! <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The bastard - sorry for using swear words but he deserves it - had told me he had an influential friend (or relative, I'm not sure) in the Prime Minister's Office who could help me.
\par <#/>I am sure he has such a person, but instead of helping me, he helped himself. <#/>Damn him. <#/>The only consolation I have is that I'm more than 90 per cent certain that he doesn't know why I wanted to be in the team be
cause I didn't tell him the details. <#/>But, damn him again, all the same.
\par <#/>I haven't given up hope, though, that is why I am still trying to figure out another way of getting myself in the team.
\par <#/>In fact I'm half way through but, having been <-/wisened> up by the bastard (I hate him), I am not about to tell anybody how.
\par <#/>Once I get in, my plan must succeed, otherwise I will smash this silly head of mine on the wall. <#/>And once in, I would prefer remaining at the headquarters co-ordinating the d
istribution. <#/>That way, I will be able to work for both Kipatimu flood victims and the Monduli drought victims I have already dispatched my old and trusted friend Kampweku to Kilwa for an on\_the\_
spot assessment of the extent of the damage. <#/>I told him to look for certain things and ask seemingly innocent questions which will facilitate (without Kam's knowledge) my plan.
\par <#/>I didn't trust Kam with the details of the plan because Kampweku has the loudest mouth in town especially when he has gulped a few mouthfuls of the golden stuff. <#/>He will spill the beans.
\par <#/>When he comes back from Kilwa, he will proceed to Monduli and later to other drought\_hit areas for similar mission.
\par <#/>But first things first.
\par <#/>And the first task - the most important jo
b - is to get myself in the team The problem is that so many people want to volunteer for the food aid distribution team. <#/>I don't know whether this has anything to do with patriotism and the desire to help the afflicted, or whether they also are nursi
ng some hidden programmes like mine. <#/>But how could they?
\par <#/>If they do, then my task of getting in the team will be doubly difficult. <#/>That means I will have to change my approach (but not withdraw from the race).
\par <#/>Now, how do I get a place in the team? <#/>I don't have enough to do the short-cut. <#/>Besides, I am told, the gentleman - no, the lady in\_charge of the }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Feed\_the\_Victims Task Force is }{\fs24\lang2057 a no\_
nonsense incorrigible woman who takes no <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 michuzi }{\fs24\lang2057 from nobody They call her granite. <#/>Very hard and mean.
\par <#/>Of course, I have already sent out fillers to spy on her likes and dislikes. <#/>One thing is out, though, and that is booze. <#/>She doesn't touch it even with a 100-metre pole. <#/>So you can see how difficult it is to get near this l
ady. <#/>I wish she were still missing a Mr. <#/>But he is there full and firm.
\par <#/>But, well, you never know. <#/>There must be something that she is <-/mightly> interested in. <#/>All human beings are like that, and she is as human as you and me. <#/>But
 come sun, come stars; come rain, come moon; and come day, come night; I must get a place in the team.
\par <#/>You might want to know why I'm almost obsessed with the desire to be in the }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Feed-the-Victims Task Force}{\fs24\lang2057 . <#/>The reason is simple. <#/>Money. <#/>Big
 fat  money. <#/>As big, <-/infact>, as two bungalows (not mere houses) and a small fleet of cars and some few lorries and <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 daladala}{\fs24\lang2057 . <#/>If you don't understand, you must be dumb and Satan help you.
\par <#/>I said earlier that once I'm accepted in the task force, I'll fight to remain at the headquarters doing the co\_
ordination, but travelling now and again to the disaster areas north and south - and maybe west too, if famine and/or floods strike there also.
\par <#/>I will also fight to bring in trusted friends
 like Kampweku to make my operations easy. <#/>The visits to the affected areas would be useful in many ways, but the two most important are the night allowances which will be quite handsome, and two, the visits will enable me know exactly, or fairly accu
rately, the aid requirement of a particular area.
\par <#/>This information will be vital to me because I will need it in my calculations for the "profit margin", so to speak, and also that the field officers do not cheat on me much
\par For example, if village X has
 500 starving residents, your list will show 5000 villagers. <#/>Your list will not show how many infants and children there are in the village, because revealing this number would mean less share. <#/>Surely, you will need a little greasing the local sup
ervisors.
\par <#/>Again, at the headquarters, you say the 5000 people need six bags of beans for two weeks when they may need only two. <#/>You can easily explain away the extra (if someone gets wise and asks uncomfortable questions) by saying it was for emerge
ncy cases. <#/>It is hard to control the movement of people, especially when they are suffering from hunger.
\par <#/>In short, in this way (and in many other ways) you will very soon find out that you need a whole <ea/>godown to store the extra bags. <#/>Now, 
if you also don't know how to turn the bags into bungalows or cars, or hard currency, you better not join the game, and if some of us do please don't make noise. <#/>Sew your mouth shut}{\i\fs24\lang2057 . <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 <ea_>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
Kufa kufaana, }{\v\fs24\lang2057 eti}{\fs24\lang2057 <ea/>.</I>
