\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <h> <#/>Lizards in a handbag </h>
\par <#/>I am one of those few lucky people with an in-born talent to earn a living illegally, and not being caught in the process }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>Please do not give this useless piece of information to the man in charge of affairs conducted from a building opposite Posta House in Dar es Salaam.
\par <#/>You see - obviously you do because you would not be reading this if you had been blind - the man is number three in the line-up of men I fear and respect most, after my father and my landlord.
\par <#/>If ever the man got to know how I earn my living, he would give me 168 hours (or seven days) to account 
for my sins, or else fly to the UK - short for Ukonga - for an unpleasant three-year holiday that involves a lot of <ea/>shamba work (without being paid for it) and eating a few half-cooked beans (without paying for them).
\par <#/>The man is thus someone from whom I would like to keep a safe distance, just like the man who is fourth in the line-up, but one whom I only fear but <-_does><+_do> not respect - the hopeless }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Mchochezi }{\fs24\lang2057 
who insists that I should pay him the 2,000/- 1 owe him, but which I don't have the will-power to repay.
\par <#/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Mchochezi }{\fs24\lang2057 lent me the money which enabled me to pay two months' rent six months ago and thereby stopped my landlord from evicting me from his room.
\par <#/>The landlord is an old man who uses half-Hitler methods to rule his tenants.
\par <#/>Once, in the backyard of the house I shook the hands of his fourth, <-/teenaged> wife and smiled a bit while doing so and the landlord happened to be passing by.
\par <#/>I swore that it was an innocent gesture of good neighbourliness (a big lie of course) but the man wasn't convinced. <#/>He imposed upon me, }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>punct}{\fs24\lang2057 
 a punishment of filling up his two spare drums of water and banned me from not just touching her hands but looking at her.
\par <#/>If only he knew that out of sympathy for the tough punishment, she 
secretly let me do to her something better (or is it worse? <#/>) than shaking her hands and saying "Hello," he would have not only kicked me out of his room but would have employed his idle extra-sharp <ea/>panga to do justice to my head or neck; or, bet
ter still, to chop off the offensive object from <-_by><+_my> body.
\par <#/>Well, I am a thief, but not the harmful type who apply maximum violence and use deadly weapons like guns to rob people of very valuable things like cars. <#/>I am a harmless thief who <
-_apply><+_applies> minimum violence (a half-starving thief can't be strong, anyway) and uses non-deadly fingers and hands to snatch lowly-valued ladies' handbags.
\par <#/>You've guessed correctly why I target ladies - they are soft and would not fight me. <#/>If the worst came to the worst, I would simply throw away a handbag and engage in a bit of <ea_>Juma Ikangaaism<ea/>: Flee from the scene as fast as possible.

\par <#/>Sometimes I snatch handbags from mean women who keep only identity cards, tiny mirrors and combs there, or put in stupid amounts like 100/- or 200/-.
\par <#/>Sometimes, I snatch handbags of intelligent women who put enough money into them, }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>punct}{\fs24\lang2057  to enable me to live comfortably.
\par <#/>But the other day, I snatched a handbag from a lady who is neither mean nor intelligent but simply criminal.
\par <#/>The lady, upon whom I pounced before she boarded a bus, was heading to a witchdoctor who had instructed her to take along certain objects, to facilitate }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_article>}{\fs24\lang2057  <-_concontion><+_concoction> of medicine f
or enabling her to hook a <-/waelthy> businessman.
\par <#/>I was terribly shocked to see a dozen dead lizards when I opened the handbag upon reaching home.
\par <#/>I am thinking of forwarding the matter to the boss in the building opposite Posta House; to order ladies to carry only money - and big money at that - in their handbags and not anything else; so that the likes of me can survive.</I>
