\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <h><#/>It pays to be a bogus diplomat </h>
\par <#/>SOME old village men are dangerous: When you offend them, the punishment they impose upon you is of a permanent nature and not the temporary type favoured by primary school teachers.
\par <#/>When you committed a serious offence, the teacher administered a few canes }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>lexeme}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 
on your khaki-covered (but underwearless) buttocks. <#/>You stood up, said a reluctant but mandatory "thank you" to the teacher, before doing two important things simultaneously: Crying as loudly as an ambulance van siren and scr
atching your buttocks as diligently as a monkey.
\par <#/>But after a few days, you forgot all about it, pending another round of caning.
\par <#/>It was terrible when you wronged a wrong old man: He cast a spell of doom upon you and this prevails till you "kiss the soil.\rdblquote 
\par <#/>This is what I strongly suspect happened to me, in respect of the boyhood terrorist incursions I made into <ea/>Mzee Mavuno's <ea/>shamba to harvest cassava in the spirit of self-reliance, not for myself but for my beloved stomach.
\par <#/>The old man's curse is apparently the source of my misfortunes, reflected in my failure to become a diplomat through either of the two main channels - training or the influence of a godfather.
\par <#/>The chain of "Fs", I scored (scored? <#/>) in Form Four exams could not enable me to gain admission into the Kurasini University of Diplomacy.
\par <#/>What's more, I don't have a godfather to forge me into the diplomatic service. <#/>But one of these days, I will commission someone to act as my human-father as opposed to godf
ather. <#/>So, don't be surprised to hear that I've been appointed ambassador somewhere, in spite of my talent as a cassava roaster (my cassava-stealing background was not in vain) plus part-time <-/pickpocketting>.
\par <#/>In the meantime, I pick bits and pieces of ideas about diplomatic behaviour and language so that when I cease to be <ea/>Ndugu and become "My Excellency", I won't be <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 mbumbumbu}{\fs24\lang2057 
 (a novice) <-_per><+_par> excellence.
\par <#/>I know, for instance, that in some instances, it is a diplomatic taboo to mention countries or individuals by name ot to describe situations in a direct way.
\par <#/>Which is why you read a statement from the government of country A, protesting against the border-area banditry perpetrated by thugs in "a neighbouring country B. <#/>" Or, a statement regretting the "unfortunate remarks" made "in certain quarters.
\rdblquote 
\par <#/>So as a diplomat-wish-to-be, I'm careful about describing the situation in which I found my friend Msimamo at the bar one evening the other day.
\par <#/>He was not cryin
g (that's undiplomatic language) but: Some watery substances were liberally flowing from his eyes. <#/>I wondered: What would drive a 40-year-old man to shed waters (not tears); unless he was mourning a departed (not dead) relative? <#/>And if so, why, of
 all places, in a bar?
\par <#/>I joined him on the table and, very diplomatically, I asked him what the matter was (not why he was crying).
\par <#/>After clearing his face (not wiping tears), he told me a sad story about how two chaps who appeared as innocent as }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>orth}{\fs24\lang2057 
 Saints had conned him of 100,000,/- earlier in the day; in the name of selling him pieces of diamonds which were in fact plain glass.
\par <#/>He lamented that he was left with only 10,000/-, which he would give to his wife, who was due to travel upcountry the following day.
\par <#/>I sympathised greatly with him and said we should all bank our hopes on Mrema's anti-<ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 tapeli}{\fs24\lang2057  battle.
\par <#/>Meanwhile, Msimamo, whose coat he had hung behind his chair, left briefly for a short call, giving me a chance to engage in primitive diplomatic service.
\par <#/>I diplomatically shoved my hands into the pockets of the coat and fished out an envelope containing the money.
\par <#/>Then very diplomatically I emptied my glass of beer and sneaked out of the bar.
\par <#/>On reaching home, I counted the money in a diplomatically excited manner, to establish if it was indeed 10,000/- because this is the balance I needed to square off my son's boarding school fees.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>It pays to be a bogus diplomat; and come to think of it, <ea/>Mzee Mavuno's curse has lost steam somehow. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X></I>
